reply.author: JATT 5ABI
reply.text:
Dhruv Rathee  Another problem with the quality of Indoor air in in India is that government is not spreading awareness about the dangers of cooking in a kitchen which is not properly ventilated. LPG when not burnt in presence of inadequate  air (oxygen) produces CO (carbon monoxide) instead of CO2 (carbon di oxide). This can also happen due to double burning.
And we all know how dangerous Carbon monoxide is for us. It is odourless makes it all the more dangerous as people do not even know they are inhaling this poison. I would urge everyone to buy a carbon monoxide detector to check the quality of air in the kitchens and take appropriate measures. Also not all indian kitchens have electric chimneys which makes it worst.
In western countries so many people have shifted to electric cooktops instead of LPG ones because of this.

Also if cooking is done in full flame and the utensil is smaller and the flames come out of the sides then more carbon monoxide is produced.

Dhruv please make video about this too. Please use your outreach to educate more and more people about this.

reply.author: Preeti Sangwan
reply.text:
No matter which govt comes.... govt alone can't do anything. Neither Money is going to do anything. Our Modern education system is only profession oriented.... people are getting educated for geting a job earning money.... there is no sense of responsiblity towards nature.
Per capita Income and literacy rates of north Indian states is comparably high....that shows money and modern education system could not bring any seNSE of responsibilty..... when i was in school we used to clean our school once in a week... and it was a very joyful act for all of us. Today the mentality is prepared by society, so called educated parents that Cleansing is the act of a 4 class employ,.... i have seen villages more clean than cities where most educated people are living which don't even through their waste into dust beans....as people have more money they have overconsumptive life styles...indirectly everything we consume as man made come from natural resources. People are not grounded to nature. If  We all are thankful to our pareNTS for delivering us in this world and nurturing us from the day we are born.... then why not we are thankful to nature from which we and our parents are getting everything for free eg. Pure water, pure air , food, good sceneries from the day we are born.
There was a deep sense for thankfulness in our culture in past. unconditional giving like a mother..... so we use to say Dharti Ma, Ganga Ma.....Now all this sense is lost....
I think Technology is enough now.... more of it and its unconcious use is going to kill this planet.

I came back to visit Bangalore in 2019 and I immediately felt wheezing and got cough and cold. text: A very crucial issue which requires a worldwide attention. Few years ago I was watching a video on climatic change and global warming (BEFORE THE FLOOD Ft. LEONARDO Di CAPRIO) where developing countries and developed countries were covered. It was explained how industries or organization being operated by wealthy individuals fund government for letting them ignore the amount of pollution that they are spreading. In China as you illustrated in your video was efforts not only made by government authorities there but was a COLLECTIVE INITIATIVE of citizens and civil society at large. \nThis vicious cycle of government not taking environmental issues Seriously is not subjected to one nation. But a strong co-relation between many developed and developing countries. \nBut time has come that our citizens demand for this grave issue which in near future is not only going to harm us but further generations to come.

author: Harsh V Sharma
text: Appreciable critical evaluation on NCAP. I'd suggest one more important point to add in the video as well as to the civil society amendments' request document that any number of Action Plans as such will not work as long as there is no cooperation between the Government and the Public. For example: Recently PM launched "Amma two wheeler yojana" in Tamil Nadu to give out 1 lakh two-wheelers to the working women "each year". If such vote-bank politics and appeasing schemes are encouraged, no NCAP can be successful.\nAnd my question to Dhruv for the suggestion to include industrial pollution in NCAP: Does it not need international cooperation? For instance, majority of Indian industrialists (forget about Jindals and Ambanis) cannot afford to buy the "patented" green technologies like Coal Gasification and so on. Right now we are able to only manage with arrestors like Electrostatic Precipitator, Desulphurisation equipment and solar based power systems in terms of air pollution (let me not talk about waste management as NCAP is not about it). Even within the existing control actions we have been facing various suits against us (India) in WTO; for example, in 2015 we lost a case filed by USA against announcing 'complete domestic production of solar panels' for which we were accused and convicted as international trade distorter. The climate experts and environmental scientists are also unable to provide solutions about this because green technologies are being linked with the business/economy. So, why don't we talk about reducing the demand for personalised-motor vehicles, indiscriminate usage of electricity and various consumer products on the public side that can avoid mushroomal growth of industries rather than fully depending on the Government? If that is the case, it hurts GDP growth figures again. Therefore it is a vicious cycle. Since this video is exclusively talking about the limitations in NCAP, I'd request you to please make any of your next videos on valid and practical solutions on ground as well as at the policy-level on the same issue. \nThank you!

author: Alok Kumar Singh
text:
Don't just blame Coal/Thermal Power Plants for high levels of PM2.5. 
Most cities you have mentioned in the most polluted list don't even have Thermal Power Plants. If Coal is the problem then by your logic cities like Dhanbad, Ranchi in Jharkhand and Ramagundam, Godaverikhani in Andhra Pradesh should be most polluted as these cities produce most Coal and have Thermal Power Plants. Companies cannot run without Environmental Clearances from Ministry of Environment & Forest Clearance (MoEFC), so they do follow set guidelines.

PM2.5 is particulate matter having a diameter of less than 2.5 micrometers suspended in atmospheric air. Even open dust/ash on roads that gets blown in air & remains suspended, can contribute to PM2.5 high values which my hometown Varanasi has a lot nowdays due to ongoing extensive development projects.

author: pratikshares
text:
While I like some of your work, this comparison with London for air pollution is wrongly placed. For couple of reasons. 

First, London had extreme pollution and filth for a very long time. It's river Thames was a dead river for a very long time. They were able to invest on cleaning it because due to the loots from their colonies. Namely India.

Second, the need to be as good as the West limits our capabilities. We need good air live and that need not be predicated on Western  examples.

One suggestion from my side to counter the problem is:
Banning of products to be sold in small satchets and plastic packages. A major part of wastes accumulated outside a general store/shop is the small packets of chips and biscuits.

Burning of these plastic packets lead to a large amount of pollution also. 

This can be one major proposal.

author: Vikas Singh
text: Its only a issue one can talk about..there is no way to prevent or control the air or any kind of pollution..sustainabilty and development can not go hand in hand..increase in consumerism and industrialization will only lead to the degrading environmental conditions. Sustainabilty is a very much subjective matter..when you talk about communities or nation sustainabilty becomes secondary..eg..if i have to lead a sustainable life style, there are many ways to reduce the carbon footprints..like i can use bycycle or public transport rather than using a personal vehicle..i can make a house which is much sustainable..with less usage of electricity..and i can keep the surrondings of the house green..but when we look at larger aspact of development like..big housing projects and industrial set up..then sustainablity becomes a low priority thing..and in developing nations like India..where industries are yet not fully grown sustainablity and pollution issues can not come into the picture..basically human desire to explore and use the every aspact of the planet is a root cause of the every kind of pollution and distruction..one can think and act in one's own capacity to reduce the pollution, but as far as the development and advancement in human life style is concerned, sustainablity is still a non existent word.

author: Ritupan Hazarika
text:
Dear Sir,
                   Please make a video on the condition of the state of Assam. The government is trying to forcefully implement a citizenship amendment bill in Assam which will give citizenship to millions of Bangladeshis in Assam and the whole state is in chaos.
          We the native people of Assam donot want this at any cost and there is a strong protest currently going on. But i don't think it will hold back the Bangladeshis for much long.
    There is already so much overpopulation and unemployment in Assam, we cannot afford these foreigners here. There is also a growing concern that we the native Assamese people will become a minority in our own land in the near future just like the Tripuri people of Tripura if the bill is Passed by the government.
       The government is trying to clarify the issue by telling us that only the Hindu Bangladeshis will be given citizenship not the Muslims.
We don't want to know what religion the Bangladeshis follow. It doesn't matter to us if the Bangladeshis are either Hindu or Muslim of Sikh or Christian or Buddhist or Atheist or even Satanic. The only thing that matters to us is that they are foreigners and we will not allow the BJP government to make Assam the dumping ground of Bangladeshis for India.
     The government says that things will change in a better way after the successful publishing of NRC in Assam. But we all know that this is another one of the Jumlaas of the government.
        Therefore i would like to request you to kindly inspect the matter and make a video on it as the media is not sharing this issue on a national level and nobody outside Assam has any knowledge of what our State is going through.
